[The 2 following reports, updated and signed on 30 Dec 2011, are
available on the website of the new Dutch Food and Consumer Product
Safety Authority (nVWA):

1. Schmallenberg virus table-form progress report, nVWA, 30 Dec 2011
http://www.vwa.nl/txmpub/files/?p_file_id=2201855.

2. A map, showing the locations throughout Netherlands of the 28
positive sheep farms, at
http://www.vwa.nl/txmpub/files/?p_file_id=2201854.

The Dutch Minister's report provides information on a positive bovine
case in Germany. It will be interesting to follow the situation (the
appearance or absence of congenital malformations) in the German and
Dutch dairy cattle herds, which presented (mild and ephemeral)
clinical disease attributed to SBV in August and September 2011.
Akabane virus was known to cause arthrogryposis (but no
hydranencephaly) in bovines during their 2nd semester of gestation.

Development of a serological test and its application in contact
persons will provide definitive information on the potential public
health aspects of SBV. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at:
http://healthmap.org/r/1r1l]
